EDA of the Red Wine Data Set by Todd Allen

Description of data set:

This red wine data set contains 1,599 red wines with 11 variables on the chemical properties of the wine. At least 3 wine experts rated the quality of each wine, providing a rating between 0 (very bad) and 10 (very excellent).

I am intersted in determining which chemical properties most influence the quality of red wines?

Univariate Analysis

What is the structure of your dataset?

The dataset consists of 1,599 red wines with 11 variables that determine the quality of the wines from the red variants of the Portuguese “Vinho Verde” wine.

1 - fixed acidity: most acids involved with wine or fixed or nonvolatile (do not evaporate readily)

2 - volatile acidity: the amount of acetic acid in wine, which at too high of levels can lead to an unpleasant, vinegar taste

3 - citric acid: found in small quantities, citric acid can add ‘freshness’ and flavor to wines

4 - residual sugar: the amount of sugar remaining after fermentation stops, it’s rare to find wines with less than 1 gram/liter and wines with greater than 45 grams/liter are considered sweet

5 - chlorides: the amount of salt in the wine

6 - free sulfur dioxide: the free form of SO2 exists in equilibrium between molecular SO2 (as a dissolved gas) and bisulfite ion; it prevents microbial growth and the oxidation of wine

7 - total sulfur dioxide: amount of free and bound forms of S02; in low concentrations, SO2 is mostly undetectable in wine, but at free SO2 concentrations over 50 ppm, SO2 becomes evident in the nose and taste of wine

8 - density: the density of water is close to that of water depending on the percent alcohol and sugar content

9 - pH: describes how acidic or basic a wine is on a scale from 0 (very acidic) to 14 (very basic); most wines are between 3-4 on the pH scale

10 - sulphates: a wine additive which can contribute to sulfur dioxide gas (S02) levels, wich acts as an antimicrobial and antioxidant

11 - alcohol: the percent alcohol content of the wine

Output variable (based on sensory data): 12 - quality (score between 0 and 10)

Total Sulfur Dioxide does not seem to have any correlation with quality.

It does not seem to be a correlation between chlorides and quality. As the lower quality wines seem to have the same amount of chlorides as the more quality wines.

pH level averages are a little lower as the quality increases. However, since the pH levels seem to cross levels for each level, it does not seem to indicate a correlation between pH and quality.

Free sulfur dioxide has no correlation with quality.

I am not seeing a clear correlation between citric acid and quality.

Residual sugars amounts do not seem to effect quality one way or another.

There does not seem to be a correlation between fixed acidity and quality as well.

Density does seem to have a low correlation in that as density increases quality decreases

Plot Three - Alcohol Effect on Quality Scatter

Description Three

Here if seems to show a negative correlation where wine quality seems to increase as alcohol percentages increase and density decreases. It looks like most of the more quality wines in this data set have volatile acidity under .4 and alcohol % above 10%.

Reflection

It seems that this dataset is lacking data in that there were not enough samples from the lower and upper quality ratings. Also, from my research the grape determines the quality of the wine more than any other feature. It would be beneficial to include information about the grape as far as harvest season, region, and type of grape. It would also be beneficial to know what type of wine as far as merlot, pino noir, zinfandel, etc. Along with the grape type and wine type, it may also be interesting to have each judges selection to see if he or she favors one wine over another. The only surprising discovery is that the volatile acidity and pH have positive correlation. Overall, there was not any overwelming evidence that would suggest the any one feature or multiples of these features have a big impact on the quality of the wine. At this point, quality is based on the expert’s subjective perspective based on taste.
